## Controllers — Per Module

Controllers are **thin routers**. Their only job:
1. Extract and validate input from the HTTP request.
2. Construct a command or query object.
3. Dispatch via `CommandBus` (mutating) or `QueryBus` (read-only).
4. Return the result directly — no mapping in the controller.

### Full controller example

```ts
// src/modules/order/presentation/http/order.controller.ts
import { CommandBus, QueryBus } from '@nestjs/cqrs';
import { UnifiedAuthGuard, RolesGuard, RequireRoles, CurrentUser, AuthUser } from '@lib/auth';

// Commands (write side)
import { PlaceOrderCommand } from '../../application/commands/place-order/place-order.command';
import { CancelOrderCommand } from '../../application/commands/cancel-order/cancel-order.command';
import { AddItemToOrderCommand } from '../../application/commands/add-item-to-order/add-item-to-order.command';

// Queries (read side)
import { GetOrderByIdQuery } from '../../application/queries/get-order-by-id/get-order-by-id.query';
import { ListOrdersQuery } from '../../application/queries/list-orders/list-orders.query';

// DTOs
import { PlaceOrderRequestDto } from '../../application/dtos/request/place-order-request.dto';
import { AddItemRequestDto } from '../../application/dtos/request/add-item-request.dto';
import { ListOrdersRequestDto } from '../../application/dtos/request/list-orders-request.dto';
import { OrderResponseDto } from '../../application/dtos/response/order-response.dto';

@Controller('orders')
@UseGuards(UnifiedAuthGuard)   // ← applies to all endpoints; from @lib/auth
export class OrderController {
  constructor(
    private readonly commandBus: CommandBus,
    private readonly queryBus: QueryBus,
  ) {}

  // ── Commands (POST / PUT / PATCH / DELETE) ────────────────────────────────

  @Post()
  @HttpCode(HttpStatus.CREATED)
  placeOrder(
    @Body() dto: PlaceOrderRequestDto,
    @CurrentUser() user: AuthUser,
  ): Promise<OrderResponseDto> {
    return this.commandBus.execute(
      new PlaceOrderCommand(dto.customerId, dto.items, user.idpSub),
    );
  }

  @Post(':id/items')
  addItem(
    @Param('id', ParseUUIDPipe) orderId: string,
    @Body() dto: AddItemRequestDto,
  ): Promise<OrderResponseDto> {
    return this.commandBus.execute(
      new AddItemToOrderCommand(orderId, dto.productId, dto.quantity),
    );
  }

  @Delete(':id')
  @HttpCode(HttpStatus.NO_CONTENT)
  @UseGuards(RolesGuard)
  @RequireRoles('admin', 'order-manager')   // ← from @lib/auth
  cancel(
    @Param('id', ParseUUIDPipe) id: string,
    @CurrentUser() user: AuthUser,
  ): Promise<void> {
    return this.commandBus.execute(new CancelOrderCommand(id, user.idpSub));
  }

  // ── Queries (GET) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  @Get(':id')
  getById(
    @Param('id', ParseUUIDPipe) id: string,
  ): Promise<OrderResponseDto> {
    return this.queryBus.execute(new GetOrderByIdQuery(id));
  }

  @Get()
  list(
    @Query() query: ListOrdersRequestDto,
  ): Promise<OrderResponseDto[]> {
    return this.queryBus.execute(
      new ListOrdersQuery(query.customerId, query.status, query.page, query.limit),
    );
  }
}
```

### How CommandBus and QueryBus dispatch works

```
HTTP POST /orders
    │
    ▼
OrderController.placeOrder()
    │  constructs PlaceOrderCommand
    ▼
CommandBus.execute(new PlaceOrderCommand(...))
    │  routes by @CommandHandler(PlaceOrderCommand) metadata
    ▼
PlaceOrderHandler.execute(command)         ← application layer
    │  loads aggregate, calls domain method, persists, publishes events
    ▼
Returns OrderResponseDto                   ← mapped inside the handler
    │
    ▼
HTTP 201 { id, status, totalAmount, ... }
```

```
HTTP GET /orders/:id
    │
    ▼
OrderController.getById()
    │  constructs GetOrderByIdQuery
    ▼
QueryBus.execute(new GetOrderByIdQuery(id))
    │  routes by @QueryHandler(GetOrderByIdQuery) metadata
    ▼
GetOrderByIdHandler.execute(query)         ← application layer
    │  loads aggregate, maps to DTO
    ▼
Returns OrderResponseDto
    │
    ▼
HTTP 200 { id, status, totalAmount, ... }
```

**Rules:**
- Inject only `CommandBus` and `QueryBus`. Never inject repositories, domain services, or handlers directly.
- Never import domain aggregates or value objects — only commands, queries, and DTOs.
- Never put `if/else` business logic in a controller. All decisions belong in the aggregate.
- Always use `@HttpCode()` for non-200 success responses (`201 Created`, `204 No Content`).
- Use NestJS built-in pipes (`ParseUUIDPipe`, `ParseIntPipe`) for path/query param coercion.
- The controller never maps the result — the application layer handler returns the correct DTO.
- **Every method must declare an explicit `Promise<T>` return type.** Never rely on CQRS bus `any`.
- **Every method must use an `@ApiAutoResponse*` decorator** (see Swagger Response Decorators section).
- **Controllers never construct `SuccessResponse` directly.** The global interceptor handles wrapping.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — injects handler or repository directly
constructor(private readonly placeOrderHandler: PlaceOrderHandler) {}
constructor(private readonly orderRepo: IOrderRepository) {}

// ❌ BAD — business logic in controller
if (order.status === 'CANCELLED') throw new BadRequestException('Already cancelled');

// ❌ BAD — maps aggregate in controller (belongs in application/mappers/)
return { id: order.id, status: order.status };

// ❌ BAD — implicit any return type
async getUser(@Param('id') id: string) {                    // ← no return type
  return this.queryBus.execute(new GetUserQuery(id));       // ← inferred as any
}

// ❌ BAD — controller wraps SuccessResponse manually
return new SuccessResponse(await this.queryBus.execute(...));

// ✅ GOOD — explicit return type, interceptor handles SuccessResponse wrapping
async getUser(@Param('id') id: string): Promise<UserResponseDto> {
  return this.queryBus.execute(new GetUserQuery(id));
}
```

